{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 21:01:45.048716", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of Network Health\n- The enterprise’s internal routing (core ↔ distribution) is largely healthy, but the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is isolated from the rest of the network.\n- End-user hosts cannot obtain DHCP leases now, and thus lose IP configuration and default routes.\n- As a result, hosts cannot reach critical services in 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS, web servers, and the load balancer).\n\nKey Symptoms Observed\n- From hosts host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1, pinging DNS, load balancer, and web servers returns “Network is unreachable.”\n- Both test hosts currently have no IPv4 address or routes:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: eth0 up but no IPv4; ip route is empty.\n  - host_2_1_1_1: eth0 up but no IPv4; ip route is empty.\n- DHCP client attempts on both hosts fail with “No DHCPOFFERS received.”\n\nEvidence Collected\n1) End-host IP configuration and DHCP behavior\n- host_1_1_1_1: No IPv4 address; no routes. dhclient shows “No DHCPOFFERS received.”\n- host_2_1_1_1: No IPv4 address; no routes. dhclient shows “No DHCPOFFERS received.”\n\n2) DHCP server\n- dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) is up with IP 10.200.0.8/24 and default route via 10.200.0.1.\n- DHCP service is listening on UDP/67 (netstat shows udp 0.0.0.0:67).\n- This indicates the DHCP server is functioning locally on the server subnet.\n\n3) DHCP relay on distribution routers\n- router_dist_1_1: isc-dhcp-relay is inactive (dead).\n- router_dist_2_1: isc-dhcp-relay is inactive (dead).\n- With relay services down, L3 broadcasts from access subnets will not reach the central DHCP server.\n\n4) OSPF state and routing tables\n- server_access_router (connected to all servers and to core_3 via 172.16.0.14/31):\n  - OSPF is configured to advertise 10.200.0.0/24 and 172.16.0.14/31.\n  - “show ip ospf neighbor” shows 0 neighbors; no adjacency is forming with core.\n  - Routing table only has connected routes (10.200.0.0/24 and 172.16.0.14/31).\n- router_core_3:\n  - OSPF has a router-id but no network statements in running config.\n  - As a result, router_core_3 is not participating in OSPF (no areas, no neighbors).\n  - Its routing table shows only connected links (172.16.0.2/31, 172.16.0.4/31, 172.16.0.14/31).\n- router_core_1 and router_core_2 routing tables:\n  - Do not contain 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - They have OSPF adjacencies and routes across campus subnets, but lack any path to the server farm.\n- Distribution routers (router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1):\n  - OSPF neighbors with core appear healthy.\n  - Their OSPF tables do not contain 10.200.0.0/24, matching the isolation of the server farm.\n\nFault Localization\n- Primary fault: router_core_3 (FRR/OSPF) misconfiguration.\n  - OSPF is enabled but has no “network” statements; therefore router_core_3 forms no adjacency on 172.16.0.14/31 with server_access_router and does not learn/advertise 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - This isolates the server farm behind server_access_router from the core/distribution planes.\n- Secondary fault: DHCP relay services on both distribution routers (router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1) are not running (inactive/dead).\n  - Even if routing were fixed, DHCP broadcasts from access segments would not be relayed to 10.200.0.8.\n\nRoot Cause Analysis\n- The immediate root cause for loss of end-to-end reachability to services in 10.200.0.0/24 is the missing OSPF configuration on router_core_3. Without OSPF on 172.16.0.14/31, server_access_router cannot form adjacency to the core, and 10.200.0.0/24 is not distributed into the OSPF domain. Consequently:\n  - Distribution and core routers have no route to 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Hosts cannot reach DNS, load balancer, or web servers.\n- The inability of hosts to obtain or renew DHCP leases is due to two contributing factors:\n  1) DHCP relay on distribution routers is inactive, preventing DHCP broadcasts from reaching the server.\n  2) Because the server farm network is not present in OSPF, even a running relay would have no route toward 10.200.0.8.\n- Impact scope:\n  - All host subnets that rely on DHCP relay are affected (hosts will fail lease acquisition/renewal).\n  - All host-to-server communications (DNS, web, load balancer) are disrupted due to the missing 10.200.0.0/24 route in OSPF.\n  - Core/distribution OSPF appears otherwise stable; intra-campus host-to-host ICMP in the earlier snapshot was functional, but services in 10.200.0.0/24 remain unreachable.\n\nMost Relevant Findings (Evidence)\n- server_access_router OSPF: 0 neighbors; OSPF configured for 10.200.0.0/24 and 172.16.0.14/31.\n- router_core_3 FRR running-config: OSPF process with only router-id; no “network … area …” statements.\n- router_core_1/router_core_2 OSPF tables: lack route to 10.200.0.0/24.\n- router_dist_*: isc-dhcp-relay inactive (dead) on both distribution routers.\n- End hosts: no IPv4 configuration; DHCP discovery gets no offers.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomalies detected:\n  - Server farm isolation from the OSPF domain due to OSPF misconfiguration on router_core_3.\n  - DHCP relay services down on both distribution routers.\n- Faulty devices:\n  - Primary: router_core_3 (OSPF not enabled on relevant interfaces).\n  - Secondary: router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1 (DHCP relay not running).\n- Root cause:\n  - Missing OSPF network statements on router_core_3 prevent adjacency with server_access_router and prevent advertisement/learning of 10.200.0.0/24. In parallel, DHCP relay services are inactive, compounding the inability of hosts to obtain IP leases.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 16708, "output_tokens": 4284, "total_tokens": 20992, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16384}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2752}}}
